17 (3) In 2019, in the case of in American Legion v. American Humanist Association, 588
18 U.S. 29 (2019), the Supreme Court of the United States further recognized that the Ten
19 Commandments have historical significance as one of the foundations of our legal system,
20 and the court also ruled that displaying the Ten Commandments on public property may
21 reflect "historical significance" and represent "common cultural heritage";
22 (4) Inclusion in our education system recognizes the historical significance of the Ten
23 Commandments in the United States and the understanding of the nation's founders such
24 as James Madison, the fourth president of the United States of America, who stated, "We
25 have staked the whole future of our new nation â€¦ upon the capacity of each of ourselves
26 to govern ourselves, according to the moral principles of the Ten Commandments";
27 (5) The Mayflower Compact of 1620 was America's first written constitution, it made a
28 covenant with Almighty God to "form a civil body politic," it was the first purely American
29 document of self-government, and it affirmed the link between civil society and God;
30 (6) The Northwest Ordinance of 1787 provided a method of admitting territories to the
31 union as the nation expanded westward and extended the fundamental principles of civil
32 and religious liberty to the territories, stating that "religion, morality, and knowledge being
33 necessary to good government and the happiness of mankind, schools and the means of
34 education shall forever be encouraged"; and
35 (7) Inclusion of the Ten Commandments in the education of our children is part of our
36 state and national history, culture, and tradition.
37 (b) It is the intent of the General Assembly:
38 (1) To apply the decision of the Supreme Court of the United States in the Van Orton case
39 to continue the rich tradition and ensure that the students of our public schools may
40 understand and appreciate the foundational documents of our state and national
41 government;
42 (2) That this Act shall not create an unfunded mandate on any public school, local school
43 system, or local board of education; and
