95 (A) Be at least 16 inches wide and 20 inches tall; and
96 (B) Include the following text, in a size and typeface legible to a person with average
97 vision from anywhere in the school facility in which the poster or framed copy is
98 displayed:
99 'The Ten Commandments
100 I AM the LORD thy God.
101 Thou shalt have no other gods before me.
102 Thou shalt not make to thyself any graven images.
103 Thou shalt not take the Name of the Lord thy God in vain.
104 Remember the Sabbath day, to keep it holy.
105 Honor thy father and thy mother, that thy days may be long upon the land
106 which the Lord thy God giveth thee.
107 Thou shalt not kill.
108 Thou shalt not commit adultery.
109 Thou shalt not steal.
110 Thou shalt not bear false witness against thy neighbor.
111 Thou shalt not covet thy neighbor's house.
112 Thou shalt not covet thy neighbor's wife, nor his manservant, nor his
113 maidservant, nor his cattle, nor anything that is thy neighbor's.'
114 (4) Each poster or framed copy of the Ten Commandments, as required in paragraph (1)
115 of this subsection, shall be displayed with a separate context statement that reads as
116 follows:
117 'The history of the Ten Commandments in American public education. The Ten
118 Commandments were a prominent part of American public education for almost three
119 centuries. Around the year 1688, The New England Primer became the first published
120 American textbook and was the equivalent of a first grade reader. The New England
121 Primer was used in public schools throughout the United States for more than 150 years
