122 to teach Americans to read and contained more than 40 questions about the Ten
123 Commandments. The Ten Commandments were also included in public school
124 textbooks published by educator William McGuffey, a noted university president and
125 professor. A version of his famous McGuffey Readers was written in the early 1800s
126 and became one of the most popular textbooks in the history of American education,
127 selling more than 100 million copies. Copies of the McGuffey Readers are still
128 available today. The Ten Commandments also appeared in a textbook published by
129 Noah Webster which was widely used in American public schools along with America's
130 first comprehensive dictionary that Webster also published. His textbook, The
131 American Spelling Book, contained the Ten Commandments and sold more than 100
132 million copies for use by public school children all across the nation and was still
133 available for use in American public schools in the year 1975.'
134 (5)(A) Nothing in this subsection shall be construed to require any public school, local
135 school system, or local board of education, to spend public funds to purchase posters
136 or framed copies of the Ten Commandments, as required in paragraph (1) of this
137 subsection.
138 (B) Each public school, local school system, or local board of education shall accept:
139 (i) Funds donated for the purchase posters or framed copies of the Ten
140 Commandments, as required in paragraph (1) of this subsection; and
141 (ii) Any offer of a privately donated poster or framed copy of the Ten
142 Commandments; provided, however, that such poster or framed copy:
143 (I) Meets the requirements of paragraph (3) of this subsection; and
144 (II) Does not contain any additional content.
145 (6) The State Board of Education shall adopt rules and regulations necessary to
146 implement the requirements of this subsection.
147 (7) The Department of Education shall publish on its public website information that
148 identifies free resources that comply with the provisions of this subsection."
