149 SECTION 4.
150 Said article is further amended by revising Code Section 20-2-1022, relating to online
151 instructional resources relating to American history for educators, as follows:
152 "20-2-1022.
153 To increase student understanding of, and familiarity with, American historical documents
154 and to provide curriculum support to classroom teachers of United States history, American
155 government and civics, economics, and social studies, the Department of Education is
156 strongly encouraged to create an online instructional resource page or pages for teachers,
157 which may include, but is not limited to, links to websites, foundational documents, and
158 lesson plan ideas. In order to create shared digital resources available to all students in this
159 state, such online resources may be integrated with the Teacher Resource Link of the
160 Statewide Longitudinal Data System. At a minimum, such resource page or pages may
161 include the items in paragraphs (1) through (11) (16) of subsection (a) of Code
162 Section 20-2-1021 and may focus on the foundational principles of limited constitutional
163 government, federalism, religious liberty, freedom of speech, the right to private property,
164 free enterprise, and the rule of law. There shall be no content based censorship of
165 American history, writings of the Founding Fathers, or heritage documents referred to in
166 this Code section due to their religious or cultural nature. It is strongly encouraged that the
167 online teacher resource page be completed and made easily available to teachers no later
168 than July 31, 2016, and support the requirements specified in Code Section 20-2-1020."
